{
  "texts": [
    "Addressing and mitigating the risk of hallucination is an ongoing challenge in the development and deployment of LLMs, requiring careful monitoring, ethical guidelines, and continuous refinement of their algorithms and training data.",
    "One of the various reasons for hallucination in LLMs, as identified by [38], is that nonsensical Out-of-Distribution (OoD) prompts, composed of random tokens, can also elicit hallucinatory responses from these language models.",
    "Some methods to minimize hallucination include SELFCHECKGPT [39], robust instruction tuning [40], knowledge injection [41], self-reflection mechanisms [42], and contrastive learning [43].",
    "While hallucination in LLMs is often regarded as a limitation and potential source of misinformation, there are several situations in which it could be advantageous if used correctly.",
    "Controlled hallucination can serve as a valuable tool in various creative and exploratory contexts."
  ]
}